SIMPLE: detain
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Detain
<hw>De*tain"</hw> <pr>(d⟦esl⟧*t⟦amac⟧n")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Detained</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Detaining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>d⟦eacute⟧tenir</ets>, L. <ets>detinere</ets>, <ets>detentum</ets>;
<ets>de</ets> + <ets>tenere</ets> to hold. See <er>Tenable</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To keep back or from; to withhold.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Detain</qex> not the wages of the hireling.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To restrain from proceeding; to stay or stop; to
delay; <as>as, we were <ex>detained</ex> by an accident</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us <qex>detain</qex> thee, until we shall have made ready a
kid for thee.</q> <rj><qau>Judges xiii. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To hold or keep in custody.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To withhold; retain; stop; stay; arrest; check;
retard; delay; hinder.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Detain</ent>⟦br⟧

